Full Analysis

Background

I am keen on evaluating the resale value of Cat Eye Chevy Pickups, specifically those from 2003 to 2006. The term Cat Eye refers to the distinctive aesthetic of these pickups, characterized by their grill and headlights, giving them an assertive appearance. I tend to focus on the potential resale value when purchasing vehicles, including cars, pickups, motorcycles, or dirt bikes. I usually opt for older models based on general observations. When assessing the resale value of these Chevy pickups, factors such as overall condition, mileage, maintenance history, modifications, and current market demand come into play. Maintaining the vehicle, documenting regular maintenance, and being mindful of market trends are key considerations for maximizing resale value. In addition, understanding model-specific details and local market factors can provide valuable insights for an informed analysis. Heres an image below:

My Case

When considering the potential purchase of this style of truck, I noticed they retained significant value despite their age and mileage. After some research, I came across information suggesting that they were produced just before emissions regulations became more stringent.

In my specific case, leveraging my mechanical knowledge, I undertook a unique project by combining two different trucks into one. I found a severely damaged truck on Facebook Marketplace, with the back of the cab and bed destroyed due to a fallen tree, priced at \(400\). However, the engine had lower mileage. Subsequently, I acquired another truck with a well-preserved body, considering it was in the rust belt, for \(2000\). The engine swap went smoothly, and I invested a total of \(2400\) to restore it to good running condition.

The purpose of this analysis is to evaluate the soundness of my decision and determine a potential selling price for the truck.

Linear Regression

For our hypothesis we will be focused on the relationship between mileage and price for Cateye Trucks. Starting out we can describe our linear regression model in the format:

\[ \underbrace{Y_i}_\text{Price} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \underbrace{X_i}_\text{Mileage} + \epsilon_i \quad \text{where} \ \epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2) \]

Our hypothesis will take a look at the \(\beta_0\) (y-int) and the \(\beta_1\) (slope).

Intercept Hypothesis

For our intercept hypothesis or \(\beta_0\) hypothesis, we aim to investigate whether the intercept plays a role in the relationship between the price and mileage of Cat Eye pickups. We have established a standard significance level of\(\alpha = 0.05\).

\[ H_0: \beta_0 = 0 \] \[ H_a: \beta_0 \neq 0 \] \[ \alpha = 0.05 \]

Slope Hypethsis

In our slope hypothesis or our \(\beta_1\) hypothesis, our null hypothesis aligns with the alternate hypothesis. In this scenario, rejecting the null hypothesis would lead us to conclude a significant linear relationship between the independent and dependent variables. Our chosen significance level is \(\alpha = 0.05\).

\[ H_0: \beta_1 = 0 \] \[ H_a: \beta_1 \neq 0 \] \[ \alpha = 0.05 \]

Our LM values

32 2499 0.6033 0.5901

When we look at the table above we see the intercept of \(15002\) and a slope of \(-0.03012\). When looking further we can see that our \(p-value\) of our intercept is \(7.272e-15\) which is smaller than our \(\alpha\) of \(0.05\) This leads us to conclude that the intercept within this situation rejects the null hypothesis implying that there is enough evidence to say theres a significant effect of the intercept. When looking at the slope we can see that we have a \(p-value\) of \(1.73e-07\) which is \(<\) than the significance level of \(\alpha = 0.05\). From this we can conclude that we can reject the null hypothesis, there is enough evidence to conclude that there is a significant linear relationship between the average price and mileage.

We can take the given values from the summary and create our mathimatical equation for Y.

$$

Y_i = 15002 -0.03012 _

$$

Non-Linear Adjustment

Cox Box

boxCox(clm)

When examining the Box-Cox graph, it appears that we have an interval covering the values of \(0\) to \(0.5\). Upon reviewing our transformations, we observe that for these values, both the \(ln_x\) and \(\sqrt{(x)}\) transformations are applicable. Therefore, we plan to test both transformations to determine which one better suits the scenario.

Conclusion

pred <- function(x) {
  exp(bl[1] + bl[2]*x)
}

pred_temp_df <- data.frame("Valuation" = c("Scrap Price", "Scrap-Price", "Current Value", "Would Sell Point"),
                           "Mileage" = c("1.65M","1M","190k","300k"),
                           "Estimated Price" = c(pred(1650000),pred(1000000),pred(190000),pred(300000)))
pander(pred_temp_df)

So, according to Brother Saunders, when using the function to estimate the value of the pickup, considering a junking price of(\(\$50\)) it suggests an extreme mileage of \(1.65M\). However, this seems impractical. The function also indicates a value of approximately (\(\$500\)) at 1M miles, which seems more reasonable as a scrapping price. My truck currently has about \(190k\) miles on the odometer so plugging that into the function pops out the value of \(\$8,337\). If I wanted to break even with the amount of money I put in the truck I would have to drive it till about 540k. Odds are I would probably sell it around the \(300k\) mile for about \(\$5.7k\) and make a decent profit. Considering the limited demand for vehicles with over 200k miles let alone 300k. Im contemplating redoing or restoring the truck to increase its value and decrease the perceived mileage. This template will help me keep track of potential selling prices and allow me to determine a suitable budget.

An important aspect to note is that some of these figures may seem outlandish. The question arises, Who would pay anything for a pickup with over 1M miles? The obvious answer is no one intending to drive it. However, its worth acknowledging that there are pickups that achieve the 1M miles club, typically equipped with diesel motors. Diesel engines have their own set of reasons and criteria that make such longevity more likely than with gas engines.

The purpose of the above table is to examine possible price points at which I could sell my vehicle and still equate to scrapping price. Its noteworthy that the maximum mileage for a pickup being sold in this dataset reaches 400k, which is still promising and suggests their capability to reach such distances. Its crucial to recognize that many other factors within the vehicles history, which are not addressed here, play a role in its overall condition and market value.
